{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445079913,"nonce":"XrOznSxNZyAGJtx/bPM8revNMbs=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODkwNzYxOQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148907619"},"message":"\u003e I know we had this discussion once before. My major objection is that by removing the header column we are modifing files in a way that they become different than the original output, only to make it 'fit' within galaxy. \n\nI see it more like we fitting them to other tools, not Galaxy. We all do the same in R and Python if we import data in dataframes, isn't it?\nThere are so many tools, especially if you are combining tools from different areas of bioinformatics (genomics, proteomics ...), that can not deal with some strange file formats.\nFor example blockbuster produces a BED-file-like output with random lines inserted starting with '\u003e'. So a mixture of FASTA and BED. I think we should change those file to fit to other tools (not because of Galaxy) to be consumed. The same you would do inside a script in which you define your pipeline, I guess. Moreover, tabular is tab separated and most of our tools work on these data. I try usually to convert comma-separated files to tabular inside the wrapper. Simply because it is user-friendly and saves the user one extra step and us as admins on extra file in our storage. And there are many other examples where we need to define a standard in Galaxy. See the BAM files discussion. In our context BAM is coordinate sorted. We need to have a special datatype for name-sorted BAM. But one sane default is needed, imho.\nAnd tabular is imho defined tab separated file without metadata. Otherwise we need to define these as comment lines. \n\n\u003e The major cause of this is of course that there is (or I am not aware of) no unified standard to present this type of data, in contrast to e.g. alignments (BAM,CRAM) or mutations (VCF). Modifying the featureCounts tabular files would not be an issue if galaxy was a completely encapsulated system (in terms of in- and output of files).\n\nThis is a matter of usability, I tend to write tools as usable inside Galaxy as possible. Everyone who can download dataset and process it with R, Python whatever can add meta data to it. Especially, if you use bioblend and can attach the meta-data columns back to the file if you like to.\nWe can always define a new file type, which can have additional features.\n\n\u003e But I think that where files go in and out galaxy this introduces problems. If a user runs featureCounts outside of galaxy (yes, these people exist!), uploads the data into galaxy and want to analyse the results in DESeq, they must modify the file (remove the header) for compatibility. \n\nWhy? The tool should be smart enough to handle this.\nIf you define your own file type you need to manually specify it during upload. I don't think this is more user-friendly.\n\n\u003e This is user unfriendly and we should have the knowledge to overcome this. \n\nFor power users yes, not for the others. (Note: I'm talking here about the general issue that we need to define sane defaults. This featureCounts example is a very simple case.)\n\n\u003e Similarly, when columns are being removed by the galaxy wrapper and a user downloads the file, it has no columns. I can imagine it is frustrating to download files and modifying them by hand again.\n\nI guess, power user can handle this. Or we can attach meta-data back to the file.\nIn the end it's a trade-off between different user groups and tool development is always such a trade-off. Do we export the Xms memory flag to the user or --verbose? Which parameters do we hide under 'advanced options'. Do we include all parameters at all? ...\n\n\u003e \u003e In general I'm not a fan of providing column names inside of the file. These are metadata and it should be treated as metadata, imho!\n\u003e \n\u003e You are right that it is just metadata, but if you reason that way we should strip bam and sam headers too. \n\nWhy? This has no implication to the usability of other tools, isn't it?\nAgain, featureCounts is a bad example but consider worse examples like the FASTA-BED file mentioned above.\n\n\u003e But here we neglect that the principal of galaxy is that it is a file based and organizing system and therefore you don't want files to be any different than if you would run the same tool outside of galaxy. \n\nI disagree. We sort BAM files by default to make it more usable. I break one-line FASTA files into 80 chars ones, just because it's more pleasant to view etc ...\n\n\u003e The metadata can still be interpreted in the back-end and I would be fan of this too, but I don't see this as a reason to strip it from the files. I know header colums are just a small thing but I think it comes with larger implications and I see this as fitting featureCounts into galaxy instead of fitting galaxy around featureCounts. \n\nAs I said, I'm fine with featureCounds this is a very simple example but there are many bad formats out there and imho we need to protect our users from this. There is a reason everyone is writing a wrapper for the wrapper of some tool (and here I'm talking not about Galaxy) :)\n\n\u003e I would rather change Tabular.py or create/find and convert to a uniform file format than to post-modify the featureCounts output.\n\nTabular does not have headers as far as I know. It can have comment lines.\nIf you want to do this you can define your own file format.\n\n\u003e Sorry for the resistace..\n\nNothing to be sorry for, I appreciate the discussion.\nFor me developing wrappers is more than writing or generating XML files. Here we have to unique opportunity to create outputs that fits in well to other tools. We can make the hand-shake happen even across interdisciplinary research. \n\n\u003e I wholeheartedly agree with @yhoogstrate reasoning. Best would be to have a header that is marked as comment, together with metadata that is equivalent to the header line. Is this possible?\n\nYes, I think so.\nStill, imagine a file with 5 headers, the 5th is the column description and now you want to sort this file. Unfortunately, these files exist :(\n\n\u003e I know this would be larger change in the galaxy codebase, but would it be possible to have \"tool-specific datatypes\"? So for example featureCounts and htseq would produce tabular output of class CountTable, which would be a subclass of tabular, which would be defined within the tools datatypes.conf? Or maybe that is already possible and I'm re-inventing the wheel? \n\nOh, yes this in discussed a lot. We can define a data type for count-data, but we can not even make this unique for htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts ;)\nI'm not sure we really want to have this complexity in Galaxy. We are working now on literature mining software, imaging, astronomy ... so many different tabular files.","files":null}]}